[normal]1. [bold]Introduction[bold]At-Bristol is an award winning science and discovery centre based on Bristol’s historic 
[normal]harbourside
[normal], and a landmark Millennium project.
[normal] At-Bristol is a member of the national Association of Science and Discovery Centres UK (ASDC).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We are submitting evidence to this select committee as we strongly believe that At-Bristol, and other science and discovery centr
[normal]es in the our national network
[normal], are playing and 
[normal]can
[normal] continue to
[normal] play a significant role in engaging the wider public with climate change. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2. [bold]Context[bold]At-Bristol’s vision is to ‘make science accessible to all’. We welcome over 200,000 visitors annually, working with diverse audiences i
[normal]ncluding families, schools, teachers and community groups. The science centre is host to over 200 interactive exhibits, allowing visitors to have hands-on experiences with science, technology, engineering and maths. Changing 
[normal]learning 
[normal]programmes, including 
[normal]science shows, workshops, experiments, competitions, lectures and special events are tailored to specific audience interests and needs.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3. [bold]Experience[bold]Since opening in 2000, At-Bristol has 
[normal]used core funds, grants and sponsorship to 
[normal]successfully engage
[normal] the 
[normal]public with emerging ‘science and soci
[normal]ety’ topics and issues, such as nanotechnology, synthetic biology and climate science.
[normal] Some e
[normal]xamples include:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Schools audience
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Public audience
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Supporting public 
[normal]engagement and
[normal] science research
[normal]&#xa0;
